# Function Parameters

When a function accepts three or more arguments, use a single object parameter instead of positional arguments. This makes call sites self-documenting and avoids argument-order mistakes.

- ✅ Good:

  ```typescript
  interface CreateTaskParams {
    dealId: number
    title: string
    userId: number
  }

  export const createTask = ({ dealId, title, userId }: Readonly<CreateTaskParams>) => {
    const payload = { dealId, title, userId }
    return payload
  }

  createTask({ dealId: 1, title: 'Follow up', userId: 42 })
  ```

- ❌ Bad:

  ```typescript
  export const createTask = (dealId: number, title: string, userId: number) => {
    const payload = { dealId, title, userId }
    return payload
  }

  createTask(1, 'Follow up', 42)
  ```

### Guidelines

- Name the params type after the function: `CreateTaskParams`, `GetEntryParams`
- Destructure the object in the function signature
- Wrap params types with `Readonly` when the function must not mutate them
- One or two positional arguments are fine when the meaning is obvious
